A game to look at and see what went wrong.  Or can someone tell me how to get rid of a bishop at h3.  Probably the answer is to avoid allowing the bishop to get there in the first place.
I began with g3 ready to bring my LB to g7 and black went with e5.
I moved my pawn to e4 and black developed his DB to e7.

Now I supported my e4 pawn with d3 and black developed his knight to d6 and he is ready to castle.  I on the other hand have not developed any pieces but I do have my DB and my queen on 2 open diagonals.
Now I develop my LB to e2 and black castles.
I develop my knight to h3 which allows me to castle but I do not have any protection for my knight.  Black then pushes his pawn out to d6 so his LB is pointing at my knight on h3.
I castled but probably should have redirected my h knight to g5 as black captured my h knight with the LB.
I move my rook out of the LB's reach to e1 and black now moves his queen down to d7 supporting the LB at h3.
I develop my LB to f3 and black moves his f knight to g4.
I move my rook to e2 to support my f2 pawn to avoid black's knight capturing it and then harassing my queen.  Black's queen moves back to d8.
I move my rook to d2 to allow the queen to move up better positioned to assist and get involved in the game. Black moves the queen back down to d7.
Now I move my queen up to e2 supporting my pawns and pieces around the queen.  Black develops his knight to f6.
I push my d3 pawn to d4 and black moves f pawn to f5.
I move my pawn to d3 supporting my d4 pawn and black captures my pawn at e4 and attacking my LB.
I capture black's pawn at e4 with my queen and black moves his knight to f6 attacking my queen at e4.
I move my queen down to e3 out of reach of the knight and black moves his c knight to a5.
I move pawn to b3 which allows the rook to protect more squares on the 3rd row.  Black moves his a8 rook to e8.
I move my knight to a3 protected by DB at c1.  Black pushes d pawn to d5.
I push my b pawn to b4 kicking the knight at a5 which moves to c6.
I move my knight to b5 and black captures my pawn at d4 and attacks my queen.
I capture the pawn with my knight and black captures my pawn at b4 with his DB.  The DB was at e7 with the rook at e8 and the rook is now attacking my queen at e3.

I now decide to exchange LB's so move my LB to g2 with black's LB at h3.  I do not want the queen to come down so would hope that black may take my LB but probably not likely.  I should instead have moved my queen and can't really say why I didn't.  And now the rook at e8 captures my queen at e3.

Needless to say I still have my LB and will not take black's as I don't want the queen coming down and attacking my king.  So I now develop my DB and allow my a1 rook to access the rest of the 1st row.  Black moves his f rook to d4 attacking my d2 rook.
I take black's rook at e3 and black captures my rook at d2.
I move my rook along where I can protect a pawn at c3 and be protected by the DB at b2.

My pieces are not easy to move into good positions.  The rook has the knight at e2 so i have to watch where I place the rook.  There is a rook at f8 so I don't want to place the rook at f1.  My DB is at b2 blocked by its own pawn at c3 and if it goes to a3 then black's DB is at d6.  I want my LB to stay at g2 because there is a pawn at d5 which I want to check the king with however there has never been a time when I can take it without black's knight being at f6 and the queen at d6.  My knight at d4 can go to f5 but the LB and queen are on that diagonal so its limited.  So I move my rook across to e1 and black knight goes up to c4 as there is nothing for him to capture from d2.  Now he can capture my DB at b2.
I now move my DB onto c1 and hope to find a better position for this piece.  Black moves his c6 knight to e4 attacking the f3 square and g4 square.
I now move my bishop down to f1 protected by my rook at e1.  Black moves his queen to a4.

My pawns are all isolated and my pieces are not helping each other.  I now decide to move my LB to c4 to capture the knight at least there is only one knight now so they can't work together.  I think I see the LB at h3 as not doing anything useful so not worth capturing.  Black captures my LB at c4.  This is really funny because this is the pawn I was hoping to capture with my LB.
I push my pawn to e4 and black moves his knight to d3 attacking both my DB and rook.
I decide to move my knight to e6 nearer to the king although I have nothing to support an attack as yet.  I forgot about the LB at h3 which now proceeds to capture my knight.
In expectation of capture of one of the pieces at c1 and e1 by the knight I move my DB to d2 so as to recapture the knight.
I capture the knight and black's LB annoyingly returns to his guarding duties!

I move my only piece the DB. to d2 to get on the diagonal and black's queen comes to d1 to check the king and with the rook at f8 I know that the game is up and its time to give in to black's unquestionable superiority.
My opponent allowed she wanted to practise playing the Colle System.  I thought I would respond with a mutual Queen's Pawn opening but I could equally well have played just about anything else.
But this is not a Colle.  It is called the Richter Opening: quite playable but leading to an entire different type of game.  instead the Colle System goes... well we'll see how it goes...

Consistent with the idea of playing a Colle but rather a conservative line.  I half expected White to play 3.Bg5 - the Veresov Attack.  You might notice that the thing would have looked like a left-handed Ruy Lopez: quite playable.  Otherwise White might have played a quiet developing line like 3.Nf3 or even something wild and woolly: 3.e4!? the dreaded Blackmar-Diemer Gambit (3.e4 dxe4 4.f3 exf3 5.Nxf3 ... with quick development for White).  Developing players wishing to hone their attacking skills could do worse than try out the Blackmar-Diemer.
My opponent having inadvertently slipped off the Colle line I figured I would play the System as if I had the White pieces.  Hence my choices for the next several moves.
Except for the 'misplaced' knight at c3 White has stayed with the Colle set up.  Now she figures the time is right for the plotted breakout.

Good move and this is the point of the Colle.  White threatens to advance the pawn to e5 (the double attack on knight and bishop is a bonus) at the same time freeing the dark-square bishop.  White often starts thinking about K-side attack from here on.
Pretty much forced if Black doesn't want the pawn to continue to e5.  Believe you me he doesn't!

Changing the guard at f6 and gaining a tempo.  But you might already be noticing something about Black's light-square bishop.  Where is it going?  Its scope is pretty limited.  Recalling that Black has been playing a 'colours reversed' Colle system we see here the downside of the System if the e-pawn doesn't make it to the fourth rank.  The c8-bishop won't be developed for another seven moves...

Not a very good move.  Normally I hold this sort of thing back until an enemy piece lands on g5 and then I might hit it with the ...h6 move.  But take a look at Whites Queen and bishops.  Their focus is very much on the K-side.  It seemed to me as well to keep the White minor pieces back for the time being whilst I completed my development.
A little bit of a counter action: eyeing h2.  Already Black was planning to fianchetto the c8-bishop and was considering castling on that wing as well.

OK...ish...! But I really thought that 12.Qd2 was more in keeping aiming the guns towards the K-side.  To illustrate the potential for K-side operations had White played Qd2 and Black castled this might have happened: 12.Qd2 0-0  13.Bxh6!? gxh6 14.Qxh6 Be7 (defending the attacked Knight) 15.Ng5 Qd8 16.Bh7ch Kh8 (NOT 16...Nh7 17.Qxh7#) 17.Bg6 Kg8 18.Bh7ch ... and a draw by threefold repetition.  If a snap attack like that was good enough to draw the game who knows what White might have developed with more preparation?
Pursuing the plan.

White has just about completed her development and casts about for a plan.  But this sortie is premature and costs a pawn.  Not disastrous White does obtain some compensatory activity for her developed pieces.  But better would have been to bring the rooks into more active positions (C- d- or e-files) and/or to play 13.c4.
Good: attacks the undefended c-pawn.
Blocking the Queen's attack.  A good alternative was to play ...Bb7 now.  Black had no time though for 15...Qxb2?? (16.Qxc6ch and White wins).

Defending the b2-square.  But White had a better alternative 16.c4! Ne7 (keeping guard over the c6-pawn)  17.Rb1 0-0  18.Bd2 ... (relocating) 18...Rd8 19.Bc3 Qg5.  Although a pawn behind White would have got quite a lively sort of game.
Even so the game is no more than roughly even right now.

A change of mind that should have cost a tempo and a pawn.  But White has discovered that her pieces are in a little bit of a tangle.  Probably Rb1 or c3 would have enabled White quickly to unravel her Q-side.  Otherwise it is hard to tell whether this was an oversight or White figuring that to get her pieces working properly was worth dropping a second pawn.
Doesn't matter:  Black doesn't take the b2-pawn!  There was no particular reason not to do so but I think I was simply anxious to get my own development completed.  After all I am a pawn ahead!
Understandable but it does have its risks mainly on account of the bishops on the d-file having no shelter there.  Black at once starts menacing them.
Placing the rook on a half-open file with a gain of tempo... Well not quite.  Black was happy to bring his Queen back...
Threatening a tactical shot based on the clump of under-protected bishops on the d-file.  How should White respond?

This turns out to be insufficient.  It is clear though that White saw something brewing!  The bishops could have been defended by tactical means: 20.Rad1! ... when 20...Nxc3?? doesn't work: 21.Bxc3 and suddenly the d3-bishop is quite comfortable and snug thank you very much!
This wins a second pawn.
Well played though Bc2 would have been slightly safer.  White keeps her bishop pair and the integrity of her structure intact.  Two pawns behind though is a big handicap.
Returning from a profitable cavalry raid to its fine outpost.

There are two points to this.  Black is planning to treble the heavy pieces on the d-file; and this rook also protects the bishop.  Black is planning soon to unmask the b7-bishop's battery against the White Queen and that of the heavy pieces against the bishop at d2.  Throughout this game so far Black has been playing a solid more or less risk-free positional style in the face of the active White pieces.
I have my doubts about this move now.  It was a bit of a spur of the moment decision.
Setting up a crossfire along the light long diagonal and the d-file.  But it would have been better played a move earlier I now think.
Nothing wrong with this!  Grabs a pawn and attacks the rook.  Now comes a tactical flurry.
Unmasking batteries against the White Queen and the d2-bishop.  Does this win material for Black?
It turns out that White had quite a strong defence: 26.Bf4! Bxf3  27.Bxd6 Rxd6  28.gxf3 ... and a reasonable game.
Now after 27.Bxd7 Qxf3 28.Rxf3 Nxd7 Black will have two minor pieces plus pawn vs rook.

Nice idea - a skewer against Black's Queen and Rook but Black can now exchange Queen for both White Rooks and the Bishop.  Much better would have been 27.Bxd7 Qxe3  28.Rxe3 Nxd7.  This would still have been a considerable advantage for Black - Bishop Knight and Pawn for a Rook - but there would still have been work ahead.
Wins the pinned bishop.  White's Queen will be no match for Black's pair of Rooks and two minor pieces.
At this point the GK engine gives ...Rd8 as better and it is true I spent a lot of time on that move.  I decided to take the conservative line as (more or less) simpler.
Black is making sure everything is protected (When ahead 'Think defence'.  That does not mean 'play defensively' though...)
White would have been better off exchanging pawns.  But really White's game is now lost.  A material deficit of minus-8 is way too much to overhaul.
This pawn could not have been stopped anyhow once it got past the enemy pawns.

So good was White's start that even the loss of a pawn didn't compromise her game. After the loss of the second pawn White began to lose ground.  It was not until move 20 that Black could point to an edge of any sort and moves 26 and 27 that the collapse really began.
Morphy's favorite response against 1. e4. Morphy delighted in piece play and there is more than ample opportunity for it in the Open Games.

(!?) - At one time thought to be inferior but revived by Garry Kasparov in some of his World Championship encounters. (It is most likely that this move will lead to the Scotch Game or even ... the Scotch Gambit.) It is certainly completely playable and abides by all the opening principles. [3.Bc4 Nf6 4.d4 exd4 5.e5  is the normal move order to arrive at the position we achieve in the game.]
(!?) - Gambiting a pawn which was common and accepted at that time. [ 4.Nxd4 is a straight Scotch Opening.] Still acceptable play today.
(!?) - White thinks to disturb Morphy's development. White has great play for the Pawn that was sacrificed.

(!) - Black does not move or retreat a well-posted piece. Instead he vigorously counter-attacks in the center! (Hitting White's Bishop.) We now have transposed to a Scotch Opening. This is actually the most common response today but in the time of Morphy it was unheard of. One of many ways Morphy played ahead of his time.
A nice outpost since the Knight is not easily removed from this square.
A bad loss of tempo. The Bishop on b5 is forced to retreat. Better was: 8.Bxc6 bxc6 9.0-0 at least according to ECO the position would be equal.
Rapid and active development! Morphy was never one to play passive moves. Notice Morphy has a threat against f2 now. And how Morphy has 3 pieces developed to Lichtenhein's one. Just amazing.

(!!) - This and Black's next move are in reality so complicated that I seriously doubt many people could have calculated this combination to its logical conclusion. Perhaps Paul Morphy was guided by his superior intuition! The move 10...Qh4 is a zwischenzug or an in-between move. This is a nice way for Black to keep the advantage.

This has the appearance of being a {halfway} decent move. GM Edmar Mednis writes in a book of his: "A perfectly reasonable move. White wants Black to capture on e4 with his pawn and thus be left with a broken pawn structure on the Queenside. After the routine 11.0-0 Qxe4; Black has at no cost to himself; the advantage of the Bishop-pair in an open position. He therefore has a very pleasant advantage." [See: "Practical {Chess} Opening Tips" page # 21-23.]
(!?) - (At least a dubious maybe even a - '?') Although this looks very natural it is the wrong move here. I believe castling is the more natural looking move for white here.

('!!' Maybe - '!!!') - This had to be calculated VERY precisely. (In some variations - in order to reach an evaluation that is beyond dispute - you sometimes had to calculate more than 15 moves ahead. I don't know if Morphy did this though GMs are capable if I am not mistaken but instead relied on his intuition and his genius. We do know from various reliable eyewitness reports that Morphy could calculate 5-7 moves ahead very rapidly. We will never know exactly how far ahead Morphy did calculate however.)
(!) - Black fearlessly continues the attack.

This is pretty much forced and shows just what a strong player Lichtenhein was. [Goldsby notes Qxc6? is NOT a suitable option for white due to 14.Qxc6+ Bd7; 15.Qxa8+ Ke7; 16.g3 Bxf2+; 17.Kxf2 e3+; 18.Ke1 Qb4+; 19.c3 Qxb2; 20.Qxh8 (or 20.Qe4 Qc1+; 21.Ke2 Bb5+;  with a winning attack.)  20...Qf2+; 21.Kd1 Ba4+;  22. Kc1 Qc2#. ]
Black attacks even while retreating. (He now threatens Qd1#.)
This is MUCH better than Qxh1.
(!!) To note: Black has other ways to win here but this is clearly the best! AND the quickest!
(!) - Black offers to give away BOTH Rooks. (The first with check.)
Classic Morphy - Attack sac protect (the king usually by castling but not this time) and mate
White's Q is hanging and Black threatens mate in one - three different ways! So white resigns.
C89 The Marshall Attack with 13.d3 (or 12.d3 as the two moves often prove interchangeable) is considered to be a good option for White to the usual 12.d4 Bd6 main lines.
Black can "chicken" out here with 8...d6 and avoid the very tactical Marshall Attack.
A standard position.
This is probably a good try against 13.d3.
Two options for White would be 14.Nd2 and 14.Bxd5.

Note that 14...Qh4 was chosen by Carlsen at Wijk aan Zee 2016 versus Wei and ended in a draw after White's 44th move.  The game move 14...Qf6 was not well regarded by my opponent in our post game discussions.  Nevertheless despite Jan's protestations to the contrary I think the move is playable and not very damaging to Black's position.  There is coverage of 14...Qf6 in Victor Bologan's on page 282 of the New in Chess publication "Bologan's Ruy Lopez" which is a Black side repertoire book.  However there is noner in David Vigorito's somewhat older "Understanding the Marshall Attack" (2010).  If you ever wonder who needs a good database you have an answer.  My guess for a good alternative to 14...Qf6 would lead to 14...Rfe8 which John Nunn and Tim Harding analyze to a "drawn" ending in their seminal "The Marshall Attack" (Batsford 1990) on page 108.  Again no coverage of 14...Qf6. Nunn-Harding state 14..Qd7 is bad based on Smagin - Geller Moscow GMA 1989.  I did no research to see if their assessment has been overturned.  A point ripe for home analysis!
15.Nd2 is the alternative here.
Okay this game is part of a thematic tournament.  I want to experiment a little WITHOUT using a chess engine.  Usual is this move or 16.Be3 but next move....
Appears to be untried in this position.  Bologan likes 16...Bxf4 and analyzes to an end game which he considers slightly better for White.
Stockfish 7 in the post mortem suggests 17...Bf8 as best.  Perhaps 17...d4 is interesting too?
Black's compromised pawn structure will probably be a long term liability.
Black still dreams of the attack...
Perhaps 22..Kh8 and then 23...Rg8.  Basically Black is a tempo too slow.
White proves the Black offensive is too slow.
Maybe 25...Bd3 is more hopeful.

The White King appears fully able to penetrate the Queenside and capture the pawn island to force a victory rather quickly.  The GK computer gives Black up for lost at 14...Qf6 but there is more to the position.  Analysis of the game with a better chess engine might prove interesting.
I did not appreciated the danger of an opposing pawn at h4 which assisted my opponent in the endgame.
We mirrored each others moves at the start with d4 and d5 and then I moved Nf3 and black went with Nf6.
I moved pawn to c4 attacking black's pawn at d5 and black developed his knight to Nd7.
I now moved knight to c3 and black moved pawn to b6 allowing his bishop to fianchetto.
I moved my DB to f4 in anticipation of moving my pawn to e4 and then e5 so this bishop was there to protect the e5 square.  Black moved his LB to b7.

i now moved my f3 knight to the e5 square as I wanted to surprise my opponent with an early attack on his 7th row.  Black moved his f6 knight to h5 attacking my DB at f4.  He could have captured my knight with his knight at d7 but he would have been recaptured by my pawn at d4 and my DB at f4.
I knew my DB was at risk from the h5 knight and I decided to push my e pawn to e3 and black took my DB with his h5 knight.
I retook the knight and black took my c4 pawn.  This left me with doubled pawns on the f file which can be useful protection once the king is castled.
I pushed my pawn at f2 to f3 and black moved his knight down to e5 supporting the c4 pawn.
I took the e5 knight with my pawn at d4 and black moved his pawn to e6 allowing his DB access to the diagonal to a3.  I now have my pawn at e5.  Yesss

Now I moved my LB out to e2 to protect my king as there are no pawns to protect the king now and d file is open. Black moved his DB to e7 in front of his king and he now has access to 2 diagonals one to a3 and one to h3.
I push my pawn to a3 and black castles.
I castle and black pushes his f pawn to f5.  I think the attack is on.  Black has the DB at e7 and the queen at d8 so they are both pointing to h4.
I decide to move my pawn to h3 and black moves his pawn to h5.
Now I move my g pawn up to g4 and black captures with his pawn at f5.

Now I recapture with my doubled pawn at f3 and this undoubles them.  Black moves his pawn down to h4 but this can go no further and I think that I am safe from any further pawn storms and black only has one pawn now at g7.
So that attack has stopped on the g file.  Now I move my queen out of the black queen's reach to c2 and black moves his queen down to d4 and checks the king.

My queen is protecting my bishop at e2 and my knight at c3 and the rooks are protecting the 1st row.  I move my king over to h2 and out of check.  Black moves rook down to f4 and this file is protected by my rook at f1.  However the black queen is also on the 4th row at d4.
So I decide to move my rook to f3 and this means that the black rook will have to come down to the 3rd row to capture my rook.  The f3 square is protected by my LB at e2.
So I capture the rook at f3 and the queen moves across to f4 to check my king.

I moved the king out of check to g2 (wrong!!) as I knew the queen was on the same row so would intervene if the black queen moved down onto 2nd row.   Now black queen captures my LB at f3 checking me again.  I think I must have forgotten that the LB is way up at b7 and now the queen is protected by this piece.

This is where I did not foresee the use of the pawn at h4.  As if I had moved my king to g1 on the last move then my queen would have been able to defend and there is the rook at a1.  So black queen moved to g3 and its checkmate.
My favourite opening
I get relieved when my opponent dosent reply me with the sicilian defence
Hmmm it looks like I would be facing the philidor defence today
I just prefer this move to the immediate d4.. I hope to mount a quick attack on f7
While my opponent makes passive defensive moves I continue to develop... I'm also hoping for a legal-like mate if my opponent plays Bg4 next and goes greedy capturing my queen after I play Nxe5
Ok no more messing around let's open this game up
After some exchanges my queen becomes centralized.. I'm loving my position now
I must say the Bd7 dosent do my opponent any good. He should have played Be7 in preparation for castling....
A good move which threatens to open up the e-file completely
Check! Personally I don't think black should have played dxe5...
.... An error I think. This moves ensures I clamp down his position even more
!! Excellent... Now the bind becomes stronger as now my opponent can't castle and his queen is tied to the defence of the bishop on e7
Probably not the best continuation from me but for the mean time I threaten to win a pawn
... And with this move I pin a 3rd piece (both bishops and the f6 knight)... The f6 knight isn't pinned but it is tied to the defence of g7
My opponent should be thinking about how to break one of the pins in his territory instead of kicking my bishop... He should try something like 13. Kf8 releasing both knight and bishop at once

I expected a5 from my opponent but instead he played this.. I must say that we had just 60seconds to make a move each and he had about 7seconds left before he played this.. The cool thing is this move helped me form a tactic.....
My opponent wanted to avoid the loss of the rook but in the process he allowed me to play.........
!!!! This ensures my opponent losses a piece by force... Notice how my rook on d1 ensures the Bd7 dosent move in order for the rook to defend Be7
???? And another error from my opponent... This wasn't the best way to accept the loss of a piece
... Because now he is forced to also lose the exchange.. At this point he resigned. Many thanks for reading...
4. Nc3 Is the computer preference.
Stockfish likes 5... h6
This looks correct but it gives white a slight advantage because he can harass the queen.
A good line for black is 11... h6 12. Bf4 Rd8
Too slow.  White is up two moves in development and can play for a strong advantage wit 12. e5

Not the strongest move.  

Now 12... Qb4 13. Bb3 and black is holding on.
Now 14... Nxe4 Gets something for the exchange.
23... Nf5 is best.
By far the strongest is 24. Qc6 Nf5 (24... Qb8 25. Qxa6) 25.  Qxa8 Rxa8 26. Kf2 and white is clearly winning.
White can press his advantage with 27. Qc2 Qe4 (27... Rd7 28. Qc8+) 28. Qg2 Qb4  29. a3 Qb3 30. Qc2 Qd5 31. Rcd1 Rxd1 32. Rxd1 Qb7
This gives black a little freedom.  Black should play 27... Rxd1+ 28. Rxd1 Qc6
Now white should play 29 Qc2 Qd5 (Qf3 30. Bf2 Ne3 31. Qc6 with no problems.) 30. Rd1 Qb7

This willingness to trade fails by giving Black too many checks. 

Best for black is 29... Bxc5 30. Rxc5 Qb1+ 31. Qf1 (31.  Kg2 Qe4+ 32. Kh3 Ne3) 31... Qxb2
The computer thinks that this gives white a winning game.  However the resulting position is so difficult to play that it is very hard for white to win.

Chases the knight where it wants to go. 

Instead the computer move now is 31. a3  How exactly this helps white or how he can make progress is not clear here.  Then after Nd5 I gave this position to the computer to play out and it had such a hard time finding a win that I assumed that the game must be a draw.  

After moving somewhat aimlessly for about 100 moves the computer finally pushed g4 and f5 to reach a winning but difficult endgame that resulted in checkmate around move 180.  That is how difficult this position is.
Best now is 32. Re1.  If Qf3? then 33. Qd4 and for the moment the black queen is stuck. Qg4 34. Kg2 g5 35. h3 Qf5 36. fxg5 Qxg5 37. Qg4
Now 33...  Nb4 34. Qb1 Qf3+ 35. Kg1 Qe3+ 36. Kg2 Qe2+ is a draw.
According to the computer 36. Qe2 would have maintained some advantage but it is hard to see how white can make progress.
Now 37... h6 holds.  Then no good is 38. f5 Qxe5
Gives white an advantage.
If 38... exf5 39. gxf5 Nc7 40. e6 Nxe6 (40...  fxe6 41. Qc3+) 41. fxe6 Qxe6 42. Qc3+ with a winning game.

Wrong. 

Correct was 39. fxe6 Nf4 (39... fxe6 40. Qf8#) 40. e7 Qd7 41. Qxf4 Qxe7 42. Qf6+
Now black can hold the game with 40...  Nb4 41. Qf3 Nd5  42. Qa3+ Nb4
Now by far the best move is ...
Black resigns
This move is the common opening move in the Nimzo-Larsen Attack although white can also start with Nf3. The alternate move Nf3 prevents black from moving e5 which is black's strongest response to b3.
Black is eager to take control of the center.
The bishop is preparing for fianchetto already with significant pressure on the central e5 pawn. Interesting to note that the DSB and the e5 pawn are locked in tension for much of the game.
Black responds with a typical knight development move defending the pawn and staking claim on the dark central squares.

There are multiple variations after Nc6. Common ones include: c4 e5 Nf3 and g3 among the most popular (not in any particular order). The move 3. e3 opens the LSB line while leaving the option for d4 keeping the opponent guessing. Having the luxury of game study I think White here is interested in increasing the LSB's scope.
Black moves in to claim more territory in the center. However this leaves the knight on c6 susceptible to pin.
White takes advantage of the weakness. This move simultaneously attacks the knight and the e5 pawn.
Black's DSB is forced to protect the pawn.
White continues the central pressure adding another attacker to the e5 assault.

Black adds the queen to the defense. One might wonder why not f6? If black 5... f6 first the black flank is open to a quick 6. Qh5+. This move is easily countered by g6 however the kingside pawn damage is done inhibiting a successful castle.
White brings in more pressure to the e5. The flank attack is building now applying significant central pressure. However white now has now limited his queen's scope a bit.
Now white can now add the f6 pawn defender without fear of the Qh5+ threat.

White brings his other knight into play. While this reduces the scope of the DSB it is a natural development move. This sometimes provides white the possibility of a discovered attack on the black king side rook although that does not occur in this game.
Black develops the LSB defending the d5 pawn.
White uses this opportunity to castle bringing the rook into play. Preparing for the eventual e file action.
Black moves to castle king side now. I do not see any other value in this move.
White begins the central attack sequence.
Exchange.
White now moves in to break up the central structure.

Black counterattacks and threatens the knight. Black might have alternatively moved d4 threatening the other knight. However this results in the black king side weakening further when white moves Nd5 and attacks the queen. I'm not sure which is the better move. I would personally not have created the isolated pawn but that's probably my personal fear at work. The isolated pawn will require constant defense attention from this point until its off the board.

White takes the knight. This is one of the beautiful things about the fianchetto'd bishop. Now with one move white has created two separate threats on the black DSB and the e5 pawn. However this move has created two weak points as well. The white LSB and the knight at e4 are both undefended.
Black castles bringing a rook to the semi-open e file.
White picks off one of the e5 pawn defenders.
Black takes the bishop doubling the pawns creating a weak pawn on c6. Notice black's pawn structure is pretty much in disarray with four separate islands.
White connects the rooks and brings the queen into the game.
Black pins the knight attempting to stop white from moving Ng5 leaving the king vulnerable on the diagonal.
White recognizes the advantage and check attacks the c6 pawn relieving the knight pin and gaining a tempo.

Black corners the king. If black moves Be6 instead this forces white to do exactly what he want to do take the pawn at c6. Moving the king and keeping the pressure on the knight forces white to address the knight first.
Which he does. Now white's knight is currently uncontested on the 5th row. This removes the threat at f3 and further pressuring the black king side.

Black brings the bishop back to guard the c6 pawn. The defensive energy required to take care of these pawns is a large factor in the game's outcome. Black has two bishops entirely engaged in guarding three pawns while white's sole bishop is fundamentally offensive.
White brings the rook to the e file to threaten the queen.
I didn't really understand this move. I would have expected Rae8 instead. I think black wanted to bring his knight into the game and eventually move h6 to kick the knight.
Anticipating the kick white brings the knight back and continues the e5 pressure.
Black brings the rook into play now. The action is on the e file now.
White brings the knight back applying indirect pressure to the black queen.
Black brings the LSB into play threatening the queen. This insulates the black queen a bit but again allows white to capture the c6 pawn.
Capture.
Black brings the knight around to threaten the queen forcing an exchange. I believe the black thought may have been to remove the strong DSB and activate the black bishop pair.
Capture
Capture
The d4 pawn isn't going anywhere no need to capture yet. Instead I think white wants to exchange the bishops if he can.
Black threatens the queen.
Moves to capture the pawn.
Black threatens the Queen. I'm not sure why black didn't move Be6. I think perhaps black was working to double his rooks on the f file maybe.
Captures the pawn. I think white could have taken the rook (23. Qxf5 Bxf5 24. Nxd6 leads to a stronger position for white I think)
Attempting to contain the queenside pawn advantage.
Discovered attack on the queen. The e file action continues.
Brings the queen back to back rank for defense.
...and rightly so... capture.
Forced.
Another threat on the queen.
Hovering around the back rank also lining up along the diagonal if the opportunity presents itself.
loading up the e file
loading up the f file and connecting the DSB
bringing the knights into the mix offensively preparing to attack the bishop with Nfe5.
Preparing for the same move Nfe5.
inevitable.
Moves the bishop to safety.
Now the black DSB is lost.
Pressures the g2 square hoping for a long shot blunder.
Capture.
Capture. Another indefensible pawn.
Making room for the king to move and adding a future attacker to the king side.
Similar thoughts on the defense.
Time to exchange the queens.
Counter check
White's earlier pawn move was timed well.
Capture although Kg8 may have left black in better position. (34. ..Kg8 35. Qxf8+ Rxf8)
Capture
Forced
White offers another exchange. I think Re7 would have allowed white to continue to collect additional material with a strong pawn advantage on the queen side.
Black retreats.
White returns to his pawn sweep.
Black attempts to defend the pawn.
White begins his queen side pawn advance at which point black resigns.

2.f4 is the Grand Prix Attack or McDonnell Attack: the latter name stems from the 14th match game played in London in 1834 between Alexander McDonnell and Charles Louis Mah de La Bourdonnais won by Black. According to Jeremy Silman and others Black's best reply is 2...d5 3.exd5 Nf6! the Tal Gambit which has caused the immediate 2.f4 to decline in popularity. White may decline the gambit with 3.Nc3 called the "Toilet Variation" so named after its reputed place of invention. A less common option is 2...e6 as La Bourdonnais played against McDonnell. Players usually enter the Grand Prix Attack nowadays by playing 2.Nc3 first before continuing 3.f4. The modern main line runs 2.Nc3 Nc6 3.f4 g6 4.Nf3 Bg7. Here White can play the positional 5.Bb5 threatening to double Black's pawns with Bxc6 or the more aggressive 5.Bc4 aiming for a kingside attack.

I move my e2 knight to f4 and black moves the queen out of the pin to f6.  However black's e4 knight is still pinned to the king by the rook at e1.

I am not proud of my next move as I seem to have forgotten I have a pin and I decide to take the e4 knight with my LB and allow black's queen to capture my queen at d4. I was able to move my LB away to c6 and check the king so my LB was safe for now although I don't know why black didn't capture my LB with his undeveloped b8 knight.  Black's king moves out of check to d8.

I push my b2 pawn to b4 checking the king who moves over to b6.
I push my c4 pawn to c5 again checking the king and it is captured by pawn at d6.

I recapture with b4 pawn and check the king again who now moves to a5.  My c5 pawn is now has a clear path to queen and is protected by my rook at c1.  However there are 2 rooks at f6 and e8 which could capture this pawn.
